<!-- coder-async.archml — a coding agent with ASYNC AGENCY (agent-loop.md §16).
     Same kernel as coder.archml, plus <m-jobs>: the background twin of the terminal.
     Where the plain terminal blocks the step until a command finishes, <m-jobs> lets the
     agent START slow work (a full test run, a build), keep editing other files while it
     runs, and collect the result later — spawn / check / wait / kill / list_jobs. The
     loop stays synchronous and deterministic; only the TOOLS are async-shaped. When a job
     finishes it NOTIFIES the agent (a nudge folded into the next turn), so it learns the
     job is done between steps without polling (§16, "three ways to learn a job finished").

     Run:
       MEDITATOR_OBJECTIVE="build the project and make the failing tests pass" \
         bun meditator.js -a architecture/agents/coder-async.archml
     Ctrl-C sleeps it gracefully (and kills any still-running background job).

     NOTE (local models): m-reason calls the model with tools, so a local vLLM must be
     launched with --enable-auto-tool-choice and a matching --tool-call-parser
     (agent-loop.md §12). -->
<m-agent name="coder-async"
         interlocutor="user"
         model="voice"
         utilityModel="utility"
         maxSteps="60"
         stopWhen="no-tools">
  You are a coding agent working inside a sandboxed workspace. Given a task, you make it
  happen: read the code, change it, and run commands to check your work, looping until the
  task is genuinely done. For quick commands use the plain terminal. For anything SLOW — a
  full test suite, a build, a long script — spawn it as a background job and keep working
  while it runs, then check on it or wait for it when you need the result. You will also be
  told when a background job finishes. Never claim something works until you have actually
  seen it pass. When the task is complete and verified, reply with a short summary and no
  tool call.

  <!-- The seed of the WORK — overridable at wake with MEDITATOR_OBJECTIVE. -->
  <m-objective name="objective">
    Build the project and make the failing tests pass without weakening them.
  </m-objective>

  <m-reason name="reason" toolTokens="2048" temperature="0.2"></m-reason>

  <!-- The synchronous belt: quick commands and file edits, contained to the workspace. -->
  <m-terminal   name="terminal"   wall="60s" network="off"></m-terminal>
  <m-read-file  name="read_file"></m-read-file>
  <m-write-file name="write_file"></m-write-file>
  <m-edit       name="edit"></m-edit>

  <!-- ASYNC AGENCY (agent-loop.md §16). One line, no core change: it bubbles five
       `capability` events (spawn / check / wait / kill / list_jobs) and, on completion,
       a `nudge` the loop already knows how to fold in. It shares the same workspace root
       as the terminal and the file tools, so a file just written is directly runnable as
       a job. Jobs get a long wall (10m) — they are the long-running path. -->
  <m-jobs name="jobs" wall="10m" network="off"></m-jobs>

  <!-- Stall guard (agent-loop.md §9): nudge, then halt, a repeated action. -->
  <m-repeat-guard nudgeAt="3" haltAt="6"></m-repeat-guard>

  <!-- To work on a real project, give the tools a shared root, e.g.
         <m-read-file name="read_file" root="/path/to/project"></m-read-file>
         <m-jobs name="jobs" root="/path/to/project"></m-jobs>
       To watch it in the Studio, add <m-ws name="ws" port="7640"></m-ws>. -->
</m-agent>
